VPatibandla Janaki of Guntur is an experienced singer. Her concert in connection with the Vardhanthi celebration of the late Mahadevu Radhakrishna Raju who worked for a long time as mridgam lecturer in GVR Gvernment College of Music and Dance, Vjayawada, was a neat and traditional performance. Radhakrishna Raju was also a great guru who produced more than 50 disciples. The function was organised by his disciples and son and well-known mridanga player Mahadevu Lakshminarayana Raju. Annavarapu Ramaswamy and K. V. Reddy paid tributes to the late mridana player.Janaki, a former student of Music College, received advanced training from  Annavarapu Ramaswamy. She started the concert withParamapurushaof Swathi Tirunal in Vasanta and followed it withAnnapoornein Sama andParasakthiin Saveri. The Saveri kirtana was preceded by fine raga elaboration. AfterKaruna Jooduof Syamasastri in Sriragam, Janaki renderedBirana Brovain Kalyani set toAdi talaminTrisra gati. Janaki&#8217;s leisurely and bhava-laden delineation of Kalyani was one of the attractions of the concert. There was efficientswara kalpanaat the end of the keertana. Theneravalalso was a highlight. After singingNeepada,  a rare keertana in Nalinakanthi, Janaki took upAmbavaniin Keeravani for the main piece of the concert. Pleasing raga elaboration and crispswara kalpanaadorned the keertana.A tuneful voice, good grasp of raga bhavas and laya precision marked Janaki&#8217;s concert. She got excellent support on the violin from B. V. Durgabhavani. P. S. Phalgun and M. Haribabu provided efficient support on the mridangam and ghatam, respectively. Thetaniwas a fine treat. Janaki closed the concert withMadhava Mamava Deva, atarangamof Narayana Teertha in Neelambari.
